            <b style="margin: 2px 7px;text-align: justify">THE MECHANICS OF REPOS</b><br />
            <div style="text-align: justify;font-family:calibri;font-size:16px;margin: 2px 8px;">
                Repo is a money market instrument. There are two usually two parties to a repo transaction. One
                party “sells” a liquid instrument to the other while simultaneously agreeing to repurchase it or
                receive it back at a specified future date. One party requires either the cash or the bond (the liquid
                asset) and provides collateral to the other as well as compensation for the temporary use of the
                desired asset(s). Although legal title to the collateral is transferred, the seller/lender retains both the
                economic benefits and the market risk of owning them. If cash is involved as it most likely is, the
                party receiving the cash will pay interest on this cash at the agreed repo rate. Economically, it
                represents a secured loan of cash where the cash investor receives the repo rate, and obtains the
                following advantages:<br />
                <ul>
                    <li>Secured investment</li>
                    <li>Repo rate competitive with bank deposits</li>
                    <li>Diversification away from bank risk</li>
                </ul>  
                Graphically, it can be represented as follows:<br /><br />
                <b>THE SALE LEG TODAY</b><br />
                Sells 100 worth of identified liquid assets<br />
                Pays 100 as cash consideration<br /><br />
                <b>THE REPURCHASE LEG AT A FORWARD DESIGNATED DATE</b><br />
                Pays 100 cash consideration plus interest<br />
                Sells 100 worth of identified liquid assets<br />
                From the prerogative of the buyer and the seller, the representation is as follows:<br /><br />
